As it's name suggests, the giant sphinx is the largest moth of this family. The forewings are yellowish grey, mottled and streaked with black and brown. There is a broad outer border of black. The sexes are similar in appearance, but females are much larger than males. These moths are on the wing at all times of the year.
As its common name suggests, this species is distinguished by havig six large red spots on each greenish black forewing.

The brown forewings strongly striped with silvery white give this moth its common name. The hindwings are bright pink at base, becoming paler towards the margin.
The forewings of this large, strong flying hawkmoth are patterned with various shades of grey and grayish white. Females are larger than males.
The forewings of this large, strong-flying hawkmoth are patterned with various shades of grey and grayish white. Females are larger than males.
The forewings of this moth are olive-brown, banded with dusty pink while the hindwings are deep pink. The underside is predominately bright pink.

The garden tiger moth has a wingspan of 45 to 65 millimeters (1.8 to 2.6 in). The design of the wings vary; the front wings are brown with a white pattern (which is sometimes missing), the back wings are orange with a pattern of black dots. There are many aberrations (pattern and colour variants), partly obtained artificially and partly by chance.

The great peacock moth is Europe's largest native moth, and as such is easy to recognize. ait has red, black and brown ringed eyespots on all wings. The wings arre brown withlight and dark bands, and the leading edge of the forewing is extensively suffused with silvery white. The sexes are similar. Other common names for the adult moth are the giant emperor and the Viennese emperor.

The great sphinx is the largest moth of this family. The forewings are yellowish grey, mottled and streaked with black and brown. There is a broad outer border of black, The sexes are similar in appearance, but females are much larger than the males. These moths are on the wing at all times of the year.

The streaked sphinx belongs to a genus of central and South American speices characterized by their long, narrow forewings. It can be distinguished from similar speices by a dark brown line along the outer margin of the forewings.
Thielaviella humicola von Arx & Tariq Mahmood
This common moth has strongly scalloped wing borders. The forewings are pale gray to purplish gray with darker bands and a darker wing border.

This distinctive and robust littleer hawkmoth has grayish brown forewings with black lines. The sexes are similar. This moth is often mistaken for a hummingbird when seen hovering in front of flowers to feed on their nectar through its extended tongue.

This distinctive and very butterfly like moth can be reconized by the yellowish white, diagonal bands on the brownish black forewings, although other forewing markings are variable. The hindwings are banded with white and have a series of square red spots on the wing.

This is a perdominately grey moth with blackish brown and while lines and bands. The wing fringes are characteristically spotted with white and there are usually 6 pairs of orange-yellow, square spots along the body of the moth.

This is a perdoominately gray moth with blackish brown and whitee lines and bands. The wng fringes are characteristically spotted awith white and there are usually six pairs of orange-yellow, square spots along the body of the moth.

This is a predominantly  gray moth with blackish brown and white lines and bands. The wing fringesare characteristically spotted with white , and there are usually six pairs of orange-yellow, square spots along the body of the moth.

This is a quite large and heavy moth with a wingspan of 50?60 mm. The forewings are quite variable from light brown to almost black. The darker individuals often have a pale streak along the costa. The hindwings are bright orange-yellow with a black sub-terminal band. As with other Noctua species (and numerous other insects), this contrast of bland-on-land and bright-in-flight is used to confuse potential predators. This species flies at night from July to September [1] and is attracted to light, sometimes in huge numbers.

This is often regarded as the most spectacular and distinctive of all moths. Its colors made it popular with the Victorians, who used its wings to make jewelry. The hindwings have numerous short and slender tails.

This large dark brown moth has sharply pointed forewings and square hindwings. The forewings each have a dark, comma-shapped marking, while its hindwings have large and irregular-shaped eyespots. Black witches have hairy bodies. Females have a pale, purplish pink band crossing their fore-and hindwings.

This streamlined moth has well camouflaged forewings, with an intricate pattern of grey and greyish brown. The hindwings are also grey with black bands, but are strongly flushed with pink toward the base. The most distinctive feature of the pink-spotted hawk moth is a pattern of crossbars which are evident on the body.
